'''Cliff Gorman''' (October 13, 1936 – September 5, 2002) was an American stage and screen actor.  He won an [[Obie award]] in 1968 for the stage presentation of ''[[The Boys in the Band (play)|The Boys in the Band]]'', and went on to reprise his role in the 1970 [[The Boys in the Band|film version]].

==Life and career==
Gorman was born in New York City, New York, the son of Ethel (née Kaplan) and Samuel Gorman.<ref>http://www.filmreference.com/film/35/Cliff-Gorman.html</ref> He was raised Jewish.<ref>http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F70A16FE3D5E127A93C4A9178DD85F458785F9</ref>

Gorman won a [[Tony Award]] in 1972 for playing [[Lenny Bruce]] in the play ''[[Lenny (play)|Lenny]]''. Although the [[Lenny (film)|film version]], directed by [[Bob Fosse]], featured [[Dustin Hoffman]], Gorman was recruited to portray a Dustin Hoffman-like character portraying Lenny Bruce, in a side-story in Fosse's auto-biographical film ''[[All That Jazz (film)|All That Jazz]]''. In 1984 he co-starred as Lt. Andrews in the film ''[[Angel (1984 film)|Angel]]''.  Noteworthy are his roles in movies like ''[[An Unmarried Woman]]'' with [[Jill Clayburgh]], ''[[Hoffa]]'' with [[Jack Nicholson]] and [[Danny DeVito]] and [[Night and the City]] with Robert De Niro.  His TV work included performances in series like ''[[Law & Order (franchise)|Law and Order]]'', ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]'' and the 1970s drama ''[[Police Story (TV series)|Police Story]]'', written by former [[LAPD]] Detective Sergeant [[Joseph Wambaugh]].

Gorman and his wife cared for his fellow ''[[The Boys in the Band|Boys in the Band]]'' performer [[Robert La Tourneaux]] in the last few months of his battle against [[AIDS]], until La Tourneaux's death on June 3, 1986.

Gorman died of [[leukemia]] in 2002, aged 65, although his final film, ''[[Kill the Poor (film)|Kill the Poor]]'', was not released until 2006. He was survived by his wife, Gayle Gorman.

