{{Infobox person | name = Joan Copeland | image = Joan Copeland.jpg | imagesize = | caption = Joan Copeland in 2011 | birthname = Joan Maxine Miller | birth_date ={{Birth date and age|1922|6|1}} | birth_place = [[New York City, New York]], [[United States|U.S.]] | death_date = | death_place = | othername = | occupation = Actress | years_active = 1945–present | spouse = | domesticpartner = | website = }} '''Joan Copeland''' (born June 1, 1922) is an American actress and the younger sister of celebrated playwright [[Arthur Miller]]. She began her career during the mid-1940s, appearing in [[theatre]] in [[New York City]], where, shortly thereafter, she would become one of the very first members admitted to the newly formed [[Actors Studio]].<ref>{{cite book|quote=At the end of the summer, on Gadget's return from Hollywood, we settled the roster of actors for our two classes in what we called the Actors Studio - using the word 'studio' as we had when we named our workshop in the Group, the Group Theatre Studio. Kazan's people met twice a week and included, among others, Julie Harris, Jocelyn Brando, Cloris Leachman, James Whitmore, Joan Copeland, Steven Hill, Lou Gilbert, Rudy Bond, Anne Hegira, Peg Hillias, Lenka Peterson, Edward Binns, and Tom Avera.|author=Robert Lewis |title=[http://books.google.com/books?id=EVVX6pynyssC&pg=PA183&lpg=PA183&dq=%22Joan+Copeland%22%22Actors+Studio%22&source=bl&ots=1a1vHo6O67&sig=V9OrIQxY7qVKpEYZRVrhEdYYHUo&hl=en&sa=X&ei=nH4yUOT0EoL30gGJu4GgAQ&ved=0CEgQ6AEwAzgK#v=onepage&q=%22Joan%20Copeland%22%22Actors%20Studio%22&f=false Slings and Arrows: Theater in My Life] |year=1984, 1996 |publisher=Applause Books |location=New York |language= |isbn= 1-55783-244-7|page=183 |chapter=Actors Studio, 1947}}</ref> She moved into television and film during the 1950s. while still maintaining an active stage career. She is best known for her performances in the 1977 Broadway revival of ''[[Pal Joey (musical)|Pal Joey]]'' and her award winning performance in the 1981 play ''[[The American Clock]]''. She has also played a number of prominent roles on various soap operas throughout her career, including [[Andrea Whiting]] on ''[[Search for Tomorrow]]'' and [[Gwendolyn Lord|Gwendolyn Lord Abbott]] on ''[[One Life to Live]]''.
==Personal life== Copeland was born '''Joan Maxine Miller''' to a middle-class Jewish family in [[New York City]]. Her father, Isidore, was a woman's clothes manufacturer and her mother, Augusta (née Barnett), was a schoolteacher and a housewife. She is the younger sister of the late playwright [[Arthur Miller]], and was briefly sister-in-law to [[Marilyn Monroe]]. She is married to George J. Kupchik, an engineer, with whom she has one son, Eric.<ref>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/26/Joan-Copeland.html www.filmreference.com]</ref>
==Career== Copeland began her career in the [[theatre]], making her professional debut as Juliet in [[William Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Romeo and Juliet]]'' at the [[Brooklyn Academy of Music]] in 1945. She made her [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] debut as Nadine in the original 1948 production of [[Bessie Breuer]]'s ''[[Sundown Beach]]''. Since then she has maintained an active career in the theatre. Her other Broadway credits include ''[[Detective Story (play)|Detective Story]]'' (1949), ''[[Not for Children]]'' (1951), ''[[Handful of Fire]]'' (1958), ''[[Tovarich (musical)|Tovarich]]'' (1963), ''[[Something More!]]'' (1964), ''[[The Price (play)|The Price]]'' (1968), ''[[Coco (musical)|Coco]]'' (1969), ''[[Two by Two (musical)|Two By Two]]'' (1970), ''[[Checking Out (play)|Checking Out]]'' (1976), ''[[45 Seconds from Broadway]]'' (2002), ''[[Wit & Wisdom]]'' (2003) among others. Copeland was nominated for a [[Drama Desk Award]] for the 1977 production of ''[[Pal Joey (musical)|Pal Joey]]'' and won a Drama Desk Award in 1981 for ''[[The American Clock]]''.
Copeland has also worked extensively [[Off-Broadway]] in New York City. Notable credits include Desdemona in ''[[Othello]]'' at the Equity Library Theatre (1946), Betty Shapiro in ''[[The Grass is Always Greener]]'' at the Downtown National Theatre (1955), Melanie in ''[[Conversation Piece (musical)|Conversation Piece]]'' at the Barbizon-Plaza Theatre (1957), Mrs. Erlynne in ''Delightful Season'' at the Gramercy Arts Theatre (1960), Leonie Frothingham in ''[[End of Summer]]'' at the [[Manhattan Theatre Club]] (1974), Lillian Hellman in ''[[Are You Now or Have You Ever Been]]'' at the Promenade Theatre (1978), the title role in ''[[Candida (play)|Candida]]'' at the [[Roundabout Theatre]] (1979), Tasha Blumberg in ''[[Isn't It Romantic]]'' at the [[Playwrights Horizons]] (1983), Mrs. Thompson in ''Hunting Cockroaches'' at the Manhattan Theatre Club (1987), Rose Brill in ''The Rose Quartet'' at the Circle Repertory Theatre (1991), Aida Gianelli in ''[[Over the River and Through the Woods]]'' at the John Houseman Theatre (1998), Nelly Fell in ''The Torchbearers'' at the Greenwich House Theatre (2000), and a part of a rotating cast in ''[[Wit & Wisdom]]'' at the [[Arclight Theatre]] (2003).<ref>http://www.theatermania.com/off-broadway/shows/wit-and-wisdom_20415/</ref> She won an [[Obie Award]] in 1991 for her portrayal of Eva Adler in ''[[The American Plan]]'' at the Manhattan Theatre Club.
Copeland began working on television in the early 1950s as a guest actress on such shows as ''[[Suspense (US TV series)|Suspense]]'' and ''[[The Web (series)|The Web]]'' and the live telecast of [[Eugene O'Neill|O'Neill]]'s play ''[[The Iceman Cometh (1960 TV production)|The Iceman Cometh]]'' in 1960. She has appeared on numerous [[soap opera]]s. She portrayed [[Andrea Whiting]] (Joanne's daughter, Patti's malevolent former mother in-law) on ''[[Search for Tomorrow]]'', twin sisters Maggie and Kay Logan on ''[[Love of Life]]'', and roles on ''[[The Edge of Night]]'', ''[[How to Survive a Marriage]]'' and ''[[As the World Turns]]''. She also portrayed [[Gwendolyn Lord|Gwendolyn Lord Abbott]] on ''[[One Life to Live]]'' from 1978–1979,<ref name="1985 Encyc">[[Christopher Schemering|Schemering, Christopher]]. ''[[The Soap Opera Encyclopedia]]'', September 1985, pg. 158-166, ISBN 0-345-32459-5 (1st edition)</ref> and later returned to the series to play [[Selma Hanen]] in 1995. Between 1993-1997 she portrayed the recurring character of Judge Rebecca Stein on ''[[Law & Order]]''. Her other television credits include guest appearances on ''[[Chicago Hope]]'', ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'', ''[[All in the Family]]'', and ''[[Naked City (TV series)|Naked City]]'' to name just a few.
Copeland made her first film appearance as Alice Marie in ''[[The Goddess (1958 film)|The Goddess]]'' (1958). Her film career has been sporadic and her appearances have been almost exclusively in prominent secondary roles. Her film credits include ''[[Middle of the Night]]'' (1959), ''[[Roseland (film)|Roseland]]'' (1977), ''[[It's My Turn (film)|It's My Turn]]'' (1980), ''[[A Little Sex]]'' (1982), ''[[Happy New Year]]'' (1987), ''[[The Laser Man (1988 film)|The Laser Man]]'' (1988), ''[[Her Alibi]]'' (1989), ''[[Jungle 2 Jungle]]'' (1997), ''[[The Peacemaker]]'' (1997), ''[[The Object of My Affection]]'' (1998), ''[[The Adventures of Sebastian Cole]]'' (1998), ''[[The Audrey Hepburn Story]]'' (2000), ''The Last Request'' (2006), and ''[[The Private Lives of Pippa Lee]]'' (2009). She also was the voice of Tanana in [[Walt Disney Pictures]]'s ''[[Brother Bear]]'' (2003).
