'''Allen Moyer''' (born 1958) is an American [[set designer]] particularly known for his work in [[opera]]s and [[Broadway (theatre)|Broadway]] [[musical theatre|musical]]s. He grew up in [[Schuylkill Haven, Pennsylvania]] and holds a MFA degree from [[New York University]]'s [[Tisch School of the Arts]] where he studied under [[John Conklin]]. His designs have appeared in celebrated productions at the [[New York City Opera]], the [[San Francisco Opera]], the [[Santa Fe Opera]], the [[Opera Theatre of Saint Louis]], and the [[Seattle Opera]]. He notably staged the world premiere of [[Stewart Wallace]]'s ''[[Harvey Milk (opera)|Harvey Milk]]'' at the [[Houston Grand Opera]] in 1995 and the world premiere of [[Ricky Ian Gordon]]'s ''[[The Grapes of Wrath (opera)|The Grapes of Wrath]]'' at the [[Minnesota Opera]] in 2007. He designed his first set for the [[Metropolitan Opera]] for their new production of [[Gluck]]'s ''[[Orfeo ed Euridice]]'' which premiered on May 2, 2007.<ref name="opera">{{cite news | url=http://www.operanews.com/Opera_News_Magazine/2009/7/Features/The_Education_of_a_Set_Designer.html|title= The Education of a Set Designer |work=[[Opera News]]| author=[[Julie Connelly]]  | date=July 2009, vol 74, no. 1  | accessdate= June 24, 2009}} {{subscription required}}</ref>   

Moyer worked for the first time on Broadway for the 1996 revival of ''[[Tartuffe]]''. He has since designed sets for ten more Broadway shows, notably winning an [[Obie Award]] and garnering [[Tony Award]] and [[Drama Desk Award]] nominations for his work on the 2006 musical ''[[Grey Gardens (musical)|Grey Gardens]]''.<ref name="opera"/> He was also nominated for a Drama Desk Award in 1999 for his set design in the play ''[[That Championship Season]]''.

