{{BLP sources|date=March 2013}} {{Infobox person | image = | name = James Saito | birthname = James Tomio Saito | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1955|3|6}} | birth_place = {{flagicon|USA}} [[Los Angeles, California]] }}
'''James Tomio Saito''' (born March 6, 1955) is an [[United States|American]] actor of stage, motion pictures, and television. He is best known for his physical portrayal of [[Shredder (TMNT)|The Shredder]] in the [[1990 in film|1990]] film ''[[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles (1990 film)|Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles]]''; the character was [[voice actor|voiced]] by [[David McCharen]]. Saito also appeared in films like ''[[The Devil's Advocate (1997 film)|The Devil's Advocate]]'', ''[[Home Alone 3]]'', ''[[Pearl Harbor (film)|Pearl Harbor]]'', and ''[[Die Hard with a Vengeance]]''. His TV credits include ''[[M*A*S*H (TV series)|M*A*S*H]]'', ''[[MacGyver]]'', ''[[Law & Order]]'', and ''[[Sex and the City]]''.
Saito has appeared in numerous stage productions, with early career work at the [[Asian American theatre]] company [[East West Players]] in Los Angeles. On [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] he has appeared in ''[[The King and I]]'', and [[David Henry Hwang]]'s ''[[Golden Child (play)|Golden Child]]''. He won an [[Obie Award]] in 2007 for his performance in [[Julia Cho]]'s ''[[Durango (play)|Durango]]'' at [[The Public Theater]] in New York City.<ref>[http://www.villagevoice.com/theater/0721,specials,76698,11.html Obie Winners announced] in [[Village Voice]] - 5/15/07</ref>
Saito starred in the regular [[supporting actor|supporting role]] of Dr. Chen in the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] drama ''[[Eli Stone]]''.
Saito graduated from Alexander Hamilton High School in Los Angeles, California.
Saito appeared in an ''[[Inside Edition]]'' segment on November 11, 2011 where a wallet with $100 was placed in various locations around New York City to see what would happen when people found it. He immediately called the number on a business card found in the wallet in an attempt to find the owner. He passed their "honesty test". Several did not.<ref>http://www.insideedition.com/news/7193/what-would-you-do-if-you-found-a-wallet.aspx</ref>
