{{Infobox person |image = | birth_date = {{birth date|1925|1|24|mf=y}} | birth_place = [[Minneapolis, Minnesota]], U.S. | death_date = {{death date and age|2011|3|22|1925|1|24|mf=y}} | death_place = [[New York City, New York]], U.S. | occupation = Actress | years_active = 1947–2008 | spouse = [[Barnard Hughes]] (1950–2006; his death); 2 children}}
'''Helen Joan Stenborg''' (January 24, 1925 – March 22, 2011)<ref>[http://www.theatermania.com/new-york/news/03-2011/actress-helen-stenborg-has-died_35381.html Actress Helen Stenborg Has Died]</ref> was an American actress of stage, screen, and television.<ref>[http://news-briefs.ew.com/2011/03/23/helen-stenborg-dies Notice of the death of Helen Stenborg]</ref> She occasionally acted with her husband, actor [[Barnard Hughes]] (1915–2006), to whom she was married from 1950 until his death in 2006; they had two children.
==Career== Stenborg appeared on stage in revivals of ''[[A Doll's House]]'', ''[[A Month in the Country (play)|A Month in the Country]]'', and ''[[The Crucible]]''; the original, belated US production of [[Noël Coward]]'s ''[[Waiting in the Wings (play)|Waiting in the Wings]]'', for which she was nominated for a [[Tony Award]] for Best Featured Actress in a Play; and the [[Lanford Wilson]] plays, ''[[The Rimers of Eldritch]]'' and ''[[Talley & Son]]'' winning the [[Obie Award]] for her performance in the latter.
She portrayed Helga Lindeman on the soap opera ''[[Another World (TV series)|Another World]]'' from 1977 to 1978. Stenborg also appeared in the 1999 film, [[My Mother Dreams the Satan's Disciples in New York]], which won an [[Academy Award]] for Best Short Subject in 2000.<ref name="NY Times">{{cite web |url=http://movies.nytimes.com/movie/300856/My-Mother-Dreams-the-Satan-s-Disciples-in-New-York/details |title=New York Times: My Mother Dreams the Satan's Disciples in New York |accessdate=2008-05-25|work=NY Times}}</ref>
==Death== She died on March 22, 2011, aged 86, in New York City from undisclosed causes. She was survived by her two children and a grandson.
