'''Alina Troyano''', better known as '''Carmelita Tropicana''', is a [[Cuban American|Cuban-American]] stage and film [[Actor|actress]] who lives and works in [[New York City]]. In 1999, she received an [[Obie Award]] for Sustained Excellence in Performance. She is the sister of the independent film director Ela Troyano, who directed ''Carmelita Tropicana: Your Kunst Is Your Waffen''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://movies.nytimes.com/movie/434320/Carmelita-Tropicana-Your-Kunst-Is-Your-Waffen/overview |title=Carmelita Tropicana: Your Kunst Is Your Waffen (1996) |work= [[The New York Times]]|accessdate=5 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C0CE5DA1F39F93AA25754C0A960958260 |title=FILM REVIEW; A Lesbian Perspective |work= [[The New York Times]]|date=19 July 1996|first=Stephen|last=Holden|accessdate=5 September 2012}}</ref> Both form part of the alternative arts scene in the [[East Village, Manhattan|East Village]] and [[Lower East Side]]. Tropicana started her career in the early 1980s performing at the WOW Café Theater (a woman's theater collective) and now performs extensively in spaces such as [[Performance Space 122]] and [[Dixon Place]].<ref>[http://www.wowcafe.org/story/ WOW Café Theater Story], ''WOWCafe.org''. Retrieved 23 September 2012.</ref> In 2010, Tropicana served as a co-hostess to [[Vaginal Davis]]' performance piece "Speaking from the Diaphragm" at Performance Space 122.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vaginal Davis|url=http://www.studiomuseum.org/studio-blog/artists/studio-visits/vaginal-davis|work=[[Studio Museum in Harlem]]|accessdate=12 March 2013|date=6 July 2010}}</ref> Tropicana often collaborates with her sister and with other performers such as [[Marga Gomez]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/25/theater/theater-listings-for-may-25-31.html?_r=1&adxnnl=1&adxnnlx=1346891014-JJXHsM30GYc4Di8obTp1hA |title=Post Plastica |work= [[The New York Times]]|date=24 May 2012|first=Eric|last=Grode|accessdate=5 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2000/04/16/nyregion/jersey-footlights-summer-stock-with-edge.html |title=JERSEY FOOTLIGHTS; Summer Stock With Edge |work= [[The New York Times]]|date=16 April 2000|first=Alvin|last=Klein|accessdate=5 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/30/arts/design/performance-space-122-looks-back-as-it-closes-for-renovation.html |title=An Auld Lang Syne Kicks Off an Artistic Diaspora |work= [[The New York Times]]|date=29 June 2011|first=Claudia|last=La Rocco|accessdate=5 September 2012}}</ref> Tropicana is openly lesbian.<ref>Carr, C. [http://www.villagevoice.com/2002-10-08/news/two-latinas-two-lesbians-two-laff-riots/ "Two Latinas, Two Lesbians, Two Laff Riots."] ''[[Village Voice]]'' 8 October 2002. Retrieved 23 September 2012.</ref> She is the author of a collection of performance pieces and short essays called ''I, Carmelita Tropicana: Performing between Cultures.''<ref>Troyano, Alina. ''I, Carmelita Tropicana: Performing between Cultures.'' Boston: Beacon, 2000. ISBN 0807066036</ref>
