{{Infobox person | name = Peggy McCay | image = Peggy McCay 1964.JPG | caption = McCay on ''[[Ben Casey]]'' (in 1964) | birthname = Margaret Ann McCay | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1927|11|3}}<ref name="ReferenceA">1930 U.S. census indicates she was born in 1927, giving her age in April 1930 as 2½</ref> | birth_place = [[New York City, New York]], U.S. | occupation = Actress | yearsactive = 1949–present}}
'''Margaret Ann McCay''' (born November 3, 1927),<ref name="ReferenceA" /> known professionally as '''Peggy McCay''', is an [[United States|American]] actress whose career began in 1949, and includes soap operas, television, and feature films. She is best known for playing [[Caroline Brady]], a role she originated and has played since February 1983 on the long-running NBC drama, ''[[Days of our Lives]]''.
== Biography == The [[Manhattan]]-born McCay was the only child of Michael, a construction company owner who specialized in building schools, and his wife, Cathryn (or Catherine) McCay. She attended St. Walburga's Convent School and [[Barnard College]], graduating from the latter in June 1949.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dramatic Composition Brings Barnard Prize|date=May 29, 1949|work=[[New York Times]]|page=28|accessdate=January 5, 2012|quote=Miss Peggy Ann McCay, who will be graduated from Barnard College next Wednesday, has received the Helen Prince Prize for excellence in dramatic composition|location=ProQuest Document ID 105824661}}</ref> After graduation, she joined impresaria [[Margo Jones]]'s Texas-based theatre company and graduated to repertory, where she essayed numerous roles. She also studied with [[Lee Strasberg]] in New York,<ref>{{cite book|first=David|last=Garfield|title=A Player's Place: The Story of The Actors Studio|year=1980|publisher=MacMillan Publishing Co., Inc.|location=New York|isbn=0-02-542650-8|page=278|chapter=Appendix: Life Members of The Actors Studio as of January 1980}}</ref> later helping to set up Strasberg's West Coast studio. One of her first off-Broadway roles was in a production of Chekhov's ''[[Uncle Vanya]]'', opposite [[Franchot Tone]];<ref>{{cite news|title=Theatre: Uncle Vanya|first=Jerry|last=Tallmer|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Ct4QAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EIwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4509,992512&dq|newspaper=The Village Voice|date=1956-02-08|pages=6-7|accessdate=2012-12-11}} To access the next page, drag the image down a bit and to the left.</ref> they reprised their roles in the 1957 film version of the play.<ref>Tallmer, Jerry (1958-04-23). "Movies: Uncle Vanya". ''The Village Voice'': p. [http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vu0QAAAAIBAJ&sjid=NYwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6477,1858143&dq 12] and [http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vu0QAAAAIBAJ&sjid=NYwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4600,1863495&dq 13]. Retrieved 2012-12-11.</ref><ref>Peggy McCay clippings file at the New York Library for the Performing Arts, 3rd floor, Lincoln Center</ref>
McCay accepted her first major role as the heroine [[Vanessa Dale]] on the soap opera ''[[Love of Life]]'', which premiered in 1951. After four years, she left in 1955 to pursue other options. In 1958 she appeared on ''[[Perry Mason]]'' as defendant Stephanie Falkner in "The Case of the Long-Legged Models". Soon after, she was cast in an episode of the [[CBS]] [[anthology series]], ''[[Appointment with Adventure]]''. She appeared in four feature films in the late 1950s before landing a lead role in 1962 in the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] television series ''[[Room for One More (TV series)|Room for One More]]'' as Anna Perrott Rose, who had written a memoir about her family life as a foster mother.
In 1962, McCay starred in the feature film, ''[[Lad, A Dog#Sequels and adaptations|Lad, A Dog]]''.<ref name="TCM">{{cite web|title=Lad: A Dog (1962)|publisher=[[Turner Classic Movies]]|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title.jsp?stid=80570|accessdate=October 22, 2009}}</ref> On February 4, 1963, she appeared as Sheriff Taylor's old girlfriend Sharon DeSpain in the "Class Reunion" episode of ''[[The Andy Griffith Show]]''. On April 9, 1963, McCay appeared in the episode "Broken Honor" of [[NBC]]'s ''[[Laramie (TV series)|Laramie]]'' [[Western (genre)|western]] series, she and [[Rod Cameron]] portray Martha and Roy Halloran, a farm couple who stumble upon $30,000 in money found inside a strong box on their property. The loot had been seized by bandits in a stagecoach heist and hidden away for later retrieval. Roy, who is bound to a wheelchair, insists on keeping the money until Jess Harper, played by series regular [[Robert Fuller (actor)|Robert Fuller]], arrives at their farm amid grave danger to all from the bandits.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0624712|title="Broken Honor", April 9, 1963|publisher=Internet Movie Database|accessdate=December 2, 2012}}</ref>
McCay guest-starred on ABC's ''[[The Roaring 20s (TV series)|The Roaring 20s]]'', ''[[The Greatest Show on Earth (TV series)|The Greatest Show on Earth]]'', and [[Jason Evers]]'s ''[[Channing (TV series)|Channing]]''. In 1963, she appeared on NBC's ''[[Redigo (TV series)|Redigo]]'', with [[Richard Egan (actor)|Richard Egan]], and on CBS's ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'' in "The Case of the Skeleton's Closet". In 1964, she returned to daytime television as a lead on ABC's ''[[The Young Marrieds]]''. When the show went off the air in 1966, she was written into the storyline on ABC's ''[[General Hospital]]'' (as Iris Fairchild) until 1970. In the 1970s, McCay appeared in ''[[Eleanor and Franklin: The White House Years]]'', ''[[How the West Was Won (TV series)|How the West Was Won]]'', and ''[[The Lazarus Syndrome]]''. During the late 1970s and early 1980s, she had a recurring role as Marion Hume in the CBS drama ''[[Lou Grant (TV series)|Lou Grant]]''. She may be best known as matriarch [[Caroline Brady]] on ''[[Days of our Lives]]''. First appearing on the program in February 1983, she signed a long-term contract with the serial in 1985 and has appeared on a regular basis ever since. {{Citation needed|date=February 2012}}
== Awards == On Monday, June 18, 1956, McCay attended the first annual [[Obie Awards|Obie]] awards ceremony, where she and two of her ''Uncle Vanya'' castmates would make a bit of New York theatre history by being among the first [[Obie Award|Obie]]-winners ever in their respective categories - Peggy for [[Obie Award for Distinguished Performance by an Actress|Best Actress]], and Gerald Hiken and [[George Voskovec]] for Best Actor.<ref>{{cite news|title=First Obie Winners Cheered at Limelight |url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Hd4QAAAAIBAJ&sjid=EIwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4489,2246685&dq=first-obie+cheered+peggy-mccay&hl=en|newspaper=The Village Voice|date=1956-06-20|page=5|accessdate=2012-12-11}}</ref>
McCay was nominated for [[Daytime Emmy Award]]s in 1986, 1987, and 2013, and in 1991 won a [[Primetime Emmy Award]] for her guest starring role on ''[[The Trials of Rosie O'Neill]]'' as Irene Hayes in the episode "State of Mind". She was also nominated for two more [[Emmy Award|Emmy]] awards, one for her guest starring role on an episode of [[Cagney & Lacey]], and another for playing the mother of [[Lawrencia Bembenek]], Virginia Bembenek, in ''Woman on Trial: The Lawrencia Bembenek Story''. <ref>{{cite news|title=''Cheers'' and ''L.A. Law'' Top Emmys: Television honors its top prime-time shows and performers.|date=August 26, 1991|work=[[The New York Times]]|page=C13|quote=This is a partial list of the Emmy winners ... Peggy McCay [for] ''The Trials of Rosie O'Neill'', CBS|accessdate=January 5, 2012|location=ProQuest document ID 108709362}}</ref>
==Personal life== McCay has never married or had children.
