{{Infobox artist | name = Donyale Werle | image = | imagesize = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = {{US}} | field = [[Scenic design]] | training = | movement = | works = | patrons = | influenced by = | influenced = | awards = [[Tony Award for Best Scenic Design]], [[Obie Award]] | website = http://www.donyalewerle.com }}
'''Donyale Werle''' is an award-winning [[scenic designer]] from [[Nashville, Tennessee]].<ref name=tca_1 />
==Biography== Werle obtained her [[Bachelor of Fine Arts|BFA]] in [[painting]] from the [[University of New Mexico]] and her [[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]] in set design from the [[Tisch School of the Arts]] at [[New York University]]. She has designed for multiple [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] shows, including ''[[Bloody Bloody Andrew Jackson]]''<ref name=nytimes_piepenburg>{{cite web|last=Piepenburg|first=Erik|title=Inside Old Hickory’s Curio Cabinet|url=http://theater.nytimes.com/2010/10/10/theater/10bloody.html|publisher=nytimes.com|accessdate=February 6, 2013|date=October 6, 2010}}</ref> for which she received a 2011 [[Tony Award|Tony]] nomination. Her design for ''[[Peter and the Starcatcher]]'' won her the 2012 Tony award.<ref name=huffington_david>{{cite web|last=Joy David|first=Cara|title=Donyale Werle and David Korins: Creating a Show's Physical World|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/cara-joy-david/donyale-werle-david-korins-set-designers_b_2523283.html|publisher=huffingtonpost.com|accessdate=February 6, 2013|date=January 24, 2013}}</ref> She has also received 2011 [[Obie Award|Obie]] for Sustained Excellence of Set Design.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadway.com/buzz/156429/ethan-hawke-laurie-metcalf-chad-deity-more-win-2011-obie-awards/|publisher=broadway.com|title=Ethan Hawke, Laurie Metcalf, Chad Deity & More Win 2011 Obie Awards|accessdate=February 6, 2013|date=May 17, 2011}}</ref>
Werle's designs focus on sustainability. She uses found objects, thrift shop finds, and many other materials she purchases second hand. She is the co-chair of the pre/post production committee for the Broadway Green Alliance. Her set design for the 2009 production of Broke-ology at the [[Lincoln Center]] featured a set built and decorated from products purchased at Habitat for Humanity's ReStores.<ref name=tca_1>{{cite web|last=Kompanek|first=Christopher|title=For Donyale Werle, It's Easy Being Green|url=http://www.tcg.org/publications/at/september12/Donyale.cfm|publisher=tcg.org|accessdate=February 6, 2013|date=September, 2012}}</ref>
==Personal life== Werle's studio and home is in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York]], where she lives with her husband Paul Jepson, a stagehand at the [[Brooklyn Academy of Music]].<ref name=nytimes_finn>{{cite web|last=Finn|first=Robin|title=Bargain Hunter on Two Wheels|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/10/nyregion/donyale-werle-set-designer-hunts-for-bargains-and-cooks-on-sundays.html|publisher=nytimes.com|accessdate=February 6, 2013|date=June 8, 2012}}</ref>
