{{Infobox person | name = Elizabeth Marvel | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1969|11|27}} | birth_place = [[Orange County, California]], U.S. | yearsactive = 1992–present | occupation = Actress }} '''Elizabeth Marvel''' (born November 27, 1969)<ref>[http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0555500/ Elizabeth Marvel profile at IMDb]</ref> is an American actress.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/14/theater/14marvel.html|work=The New York Times|first=Patrick|last=Healy|title=Plunging Into Uncharted Depths of Character|date=March 14, 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://nymag.com/daily/intel/2010/03/elizabeth_marvel_has_balls.html Elizabeth Marvel Has Balls], Daily Intel</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Del |first=John |url=http://gothamist.com/2010/02/26/elizabeth_marvel_actor.php |title=Elizabeth Marvel, Actor |publisher=Gothamist |date=2010-02-26 |accessdate=2013-03-18}}</ref>
==Early life== Marvel was born in [[Orange County, California]], but raised in [[Mohnton, Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.familytreelegends.com/records/calbirths?c=search&first=Elizabet&last=+Marvel&spelling=Exact&4_year=&4_month=0&4_day=0&5=&7=&SubmitSearch.x=68&SubmitSearch.y=10&SubmitSearch=Submit |title=Place of birth per www.familytreelegends.com |publisher=Familytreelegends.com |date=1969-11-27 |accessdate=2013-03-18}}</ref> She attended [[Juilliard School]] and since early 1990's appeared in off-Broadway plays.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cote |first=David |url=http://newyork.timeout.com/things-to-do/this-week-in-new-york/25740/elizabeth-marvel |title=Elizabeth Marvel &#124; Things to Do &#124; reviews, guides, things to do, film - Time Out New York |publisher=Newyork.timeout.com |date=2008-09-24 |accessdate=2013-03-18}}</ref>
==Career== Marvel appeared in many stage productions throughout her career. She has won [[Obie Award]]s for her work in ''[[Thérèse Raquin]]'', ''[[Hedda Gabler]]'', ''[[A Streetcar Named Desire (play)|A Streetcar Named Desire]]'' and ''[[Misalliance]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americantheatrewing.org/biography/detail/elizabeth_marvel |title=Profile at |publisher=Americantheatrewing.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-18}}</ref> She returned to the role she originated Off-Broadway of Brooke Wyeth in [[Other Desert Cities]], which was played by [[Rachel Griffiths]] at first. She will be coming back to Broadway in the revivial of ''[[Picnic (play)|Picnic]]''. In 2009, for her performance in ''Fifty Words'', she was nominated for a [[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Actress in a Play]].<ref name=Cozby>{{cite web|last=Cozby|first=Paul|title='Billy Elliot' Nabs Drama Desk Best Musical|url=http://theater.about.com/od/behindthescenes/a/dramadesknoms09.htm|work=About.com theater|accessdate=June 2, 2011}}</ref>
In film, Marvel has appeared in ''[[True Grit (2010 film)|True Grit]]''<ref>[http://movies.rightcelebrity.com/elizabeth-marvel-true-grit-actress/2291 Elizabeth Marvel: True Grit Actress], Right Cinema</ref> as the adult Mattie Ross, ''[[Burn After Reading]]'', directed by the [[Coen brothers]]. She also appears in the ''[[The Bourne Legacy (film)|The Bourne Legacy]]'', ''[[Lincoln (2012 film)|Lincoln]]'' and ''[[Hyde Park on Hudson]]''.
On television Marvel is best-known for her regular role as Nancy Parras in CBS series ''[[The District]]'' (2000-2004). She also played recurring roles in ''[[Lights Out (2011 TV series)|Lights Out]]'', ''[[Law & Order]]'', ''[[Nurse Jackie]]'' and ''[[Person of Interest (TV series)|Person of Interest]]'', and will guest-starred on ''[[30 Rock]]'', ''[[The Good Wife]]'' and ''[[The Newsroom (U.S. TV series)|The Newsroom]]''. In 2013 she was cast as lead role of CW's family drama pilot ''Blink'' opposite [[John Benjamin Hickey]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/03/elizabeth-marvel-to-star-in-cws-blink-brooklyn-sudano-cast-in-abcs-venice/ | title=Elizabeth Marvel To Star In CW’s ‘Blink’, Brooklyn Sudano Cast In ABC’s ‘Venice’ | date=March 18, 2013 | accessdate=March 26, 2013 | author=Nellie Andreeva}}</ref>
